The paper deals with algorithms for computing tree decompositions, which are commonly used in a variety of computational problems such as query evaluation and inference over probabilistic graphical models. This makes it relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including discrete mathematics (cs.DM), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), databases (cs.DB), computational geometry (cs.CG), and machine learning (cs.LG). However, given the focus on graph algorithms and optimization, we believe that cs.DM and cs.AI are the most likely categories, followed by cs.DB, cs.CG, and cs.LG.
